      {
        "number": 5,
        "title": "Two vineyards — Solomon’s rented and the bride’s own",
        "range": "8:11–12",
        "excerpt": "Solomon had a vineyard at Baal-hamon; he entrusted the vineyard to caretakers. Each one was to bring a thousand shekels of silver for its fruit. My very own vineyard is at my disposal.",
        "body": "The chapter’s sharpest social commentary lies here. Solomon owned a vineyard at *Baal-hamon* — a name meaning *lord of abundance* or *master of a multitude*. Whether or not the place existed historically, its name does the symbolic work: this is the king’s mass-scale, commercialized landholding, leased to tenants for a thousand shekels of silver per tenant. The transaction is impersonal, distant, mediated. Solomon never works the land; tenants do. The yield is currency.\n\nThe bride replies with a deliberate contrast: *my very own vineyard is at my disposal* — literally, *my vineyard, which is mine, is before me* (*lephanay*). Throughout the Song, the bride’s *vineyard* has been a metaphor for her own body and self (1:6 — *my own vineyard I have not kept*; 7:12 — *let us go early to the vineyards, there I will give you my love*). Now she declares: my vineyard is not Solomon’s to rent. It is mine to give. The thousand shekels are for Solomon, and two hundred for the caretakers — she can do the math of the king’s economy — but her vineyard is not in his ledger. It is hers.\n\nThe contrast is devastating. Solomon, the historical king who ended his reign with seven hundred wives and three hundred concubines, owned women the way he owned vineyards — commercially, distantly, in volume. The bride’s love stands as the opposite economy: one woman, one man, freely given, not for sale. The text honors *covenant fidelity* over *royal acquisition*, and it does so in the very book traditionally attributed to the king who failed most spectacularly at the first. Read this way, 8:11–12 is the Song’s deepest social critique: love at its highest is not what kings can buy.\n\nFor those who read the Song typologically, the contrast also resonates. Christ does not rent His bride from tenants; He purchased her with His own blood (Acts 20:28; 1 Peter 1:18–19) and brings her to Himself in personal covenant, not commercial transaction. The bride’s response — *my vineyard is mine to give* — is the response of a redeemed people who give themselves freely to the One who has covenant-claim on them, not because they are coerced but because love compels (2 Corinthians 5:14).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kerem* (vineyard) recurs in the Song as the bride’s self-image (1:6; 2:15; 7:12; 8:11–12). *Lephanay* (at my disposal, before me) carries the sense of personal presence and free authority — the vineyard is not absent (rented out) but present, at the owner’s own hand."
      },
      {
        "number": 6,
        "title": "Closing summons — hurry, my beloved",
        "range": "8:13–14",
        "excerpt": "O you who sit in the gardens, my companions are listening for your voice — let me hear it! Hurry, my beloved, and be like a gazelle or a young stag on the mountains of spices.",
        "body": "The book closes with a brief exchange. The beloved speaks first (v. 13): *O you who sit in the gardens, my companions are listening for your voice — let me hear it.* The gardens recall 4:12 (*a garden locked is my sister, my bride*), 6:2 (*my beloved has gone down to his garden*), and the cultivated intimacy that pervades the Song. The beloved is publicly settled in the gardens; his companions wait with him; what completes the scene is the bride’s voice. The Song does not end with a kiss; it ends with a *call*.\n\nThe bride answers (v. 14): *hurry, my beloved, and be like a gazelle or a young stag on the mountains of spices.* The image deliberately reprises 2:17 (*until the day breathes and the shadows flee away, turn, my beloved, and be like a gazelle or a young stag on the mountains of Bether*). But the reversal is striking. There she asked him to *turn* (*sov*) until dawn — a request for delay. Here she asks him to *hurry* (*berach*, lit. *flee*, but in context *come swiftly*) — a request for haste. The relationship that began with the patience of right timing ends with the urgency of mature longing.\n\nThe *mountains of spices* (*harey besamim*) are not the mountains of separation (*harey beter*) of 2:17. The chapter’s final geography is fragrant, cultivated, lifted high. The Song does not close with a couple inside a house; it closes with a couple on the heights, fragrant with the spices of mature covenant love. The image is intentionally open-ended. Marriage in the Song is not a static achievement but an ongoing motion — the gazelle and stag continue to move, and the bride’s last word is to call her beloved into that motion.\n\nFor Christian readers, the Song’s closing summons inevitably reaches forward. The bride says *hurry*; the church says *Come, Lord Jesus* (Revelation 22:20). *The Spirit and the bride say, Come* (Revelation 22:17). What chapter 8 has established — that covenant love is a divine flame, that it cannot be quenched or bought, that it seals its partners as inalienable possessions — finds its highest fulfillment in the marriage of the Lamb (Revelation 19:7–9), where the bride’s *come* and the Bridegroom’s arrival finally meet.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Berach* (hurry, flee) is the same verb used at 2:17, but here in context functions as *come swiftly* rather than *flee away*. *Besamim* (spices) recalls 4:10, 14, 16; 5:1, 13 — the fragrance of consummated love, now elevated to mountain heights. The Song’s last word is not a noun but a *direction*."
      }
